{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413170"},"attributes":{"position":9,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:58:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:58:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"565"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488873"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"565"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/565"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.47,0.03,0.15,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"565"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114724"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/565"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"565"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96727"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1147"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48289"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114724"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-month history of worsening exertional dyspnoea. It is not associated with coughing, fevers, or chest pain. He reports nocturia over the past month and shortness of breath when reclining to watch TV at night. His medical history includes untreated hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, asthma, and gout. He does not take any regular medications. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks 4-5 standard alcoholic drinks daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with no use of accessory muscles for breathing. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 160/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Heart sounds are dual with no added sounds or murmurs. There is normal air entry bilaterally, with crackles heard in both lung bases. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated. The abdomen is soft and non-tender, and the liver is not enlarged. There is no peripheral oedema, and peripheral pulses are strong bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely to improve mortality in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Furosemide","Empagliflozin","Home oxygen therapy","Amlodipine","Atenolol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient likely has heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF), evidenced by his worsening exertional dyspnoea, nocturia, orthopnea, and bilateral basal crackles on examination. The condition is likely secondary to poorly controlled hypertension and possible alcoholic cardiomyopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E, an SGLT-2 inhibitor, is the only medication listed out of the optional answers that has been proven to improve mortality in patients with chronic heart failure with reduced ejection fraction. It will also help reduce his hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in reducing fluid overload and is often used, particularly in acute pulmonary oedema, but does not improve mortality in chronic heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHome oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the few interventions that improves mortality for patients with COPD. However, this patient\u0027s oxygen saturation of 98% on room air makes this intervention unlikely to be beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E is a first-line agent for hypertension in elderly patients. While it would be appropriate to start anti-hypertensive therapy, it is not likely to provide as much mortality benefit as empagliflozin in the context of heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtenolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a beta-blocker that can be used to treat hypertension. However, it has not been proven to reduce mortality in heart failure, unlike certain other beta-blockers such as metoprolol succinate, carvedilol, or bisoprolol. Moreover, this patient\u0027s asthma is a relative contraindication to beta-blockers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that in Australia, SGLT-2 inhibitors are currently only available on the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (PBS) for patients with diagnosed heart failure with reduced ejection fraction or for those with diabetes. Off-PBS prescription may be considered after discussion with the patient about potential out-of-pocket costs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Empagliflozin (SGLT-2 inhibitor) improves mortality in patients with reduced ejection fraction heart failure.","Nocturia and orthopnea are common symptoms of heart failure.","Bilateral basal crackles on lung examination are a common sign of heart failure."],"references":["Johann Bauersachs, Heart failure drug treatment: the fantastic four, European Heart Journal, Volume 42, Issue 6, 7 February 2021, Pages 681\u2013683, https://doi.org/10.1093/eurheartj/ehaa1012","Ponikowski et al. 2016 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure. Eur J Heart Fail. 2016 Aug;18(8):891-975. PMID: 27207191."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96727"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"565"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96727"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-19T19:36:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-19T19:38:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"565"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114724"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attribute